SIMPLE: petty
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Petty
<hw>Pet"ty</hw> <pr>(p⟦ecr⟧t"t⟦ycr⟧)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos>
<amorph>[<pos>Compar.</pos> <adjf>Pettier</adjf>
<pr>(p⟦ecr⟧t"t⟦icr⟧*⟦etil⟧r)</pr>; <pos>superl.</pos>
<adjf>Pettiest</adjf>.]</amorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>petit</ets>, F.
<ets>petit</ets>; probably of Celtic origin, and akin to E.
<ets>piece</ets>. Cf. <er>Petit</er>.]</ety> <def>Little; trifling;
inconsiderable; unimportant; also, inferior; subordinate; <as>as, a
<ex>petty</ex> fault; <ex>petty</ex> complaints; a <ex>petty</ex>
prince.</as></def> <rj><au>Denham.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Like a <qex>petty</qex> god⟦br⟧
I walked about, admired of all.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Petty averages</b></col>. <cd>See under
<er>Average</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Petty cash</b></col>, <cd>money
expended or received in small items or amounts.</cd> -- <col><b>Petty
officer</b></col>, <cd>a subofficer in the navy, as a gunner, etc.,
corresponding to a noncommissionned officer in the army.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ For <xex>petty constable</xex>, <xex>petty jury</xex>,
<xex>petty larceny</xex>, <xex>petty treason</xex>, See
<er>Petit</er>.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Little; diminutive; inconsiderable; inferior;
trifling; trivial; unimportant; frivolous.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 1074 --></p>

<p><ent>Pettychaps</ent>⟦br⟧
